"use strict";(globalThis.webpackChunkportfolio=globalThis.webpackChunkportfolio||[]).push([[8130],{7735(e){e.exports=JSON.parse('{"archive":{"blogPosts":[{"id":"feud","metadata":{"permalink":"/blog/feud","source":"@site/blog/2026-03-27-feud.md","title":"Feud","description":"Strategy game with a standard deck of 52 playing cards.","date":"2026-03-27T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"card games","permalink":"/blog/tags/card-games"},{"inline":true,"label":"feud","permalink":"/blog/tags/feud"},{"inline":true,"label":"friends","permalink":"/blog/tags/friends"}],"readingTime":2.1,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[],"frontMatter":{"title":"Feud","description":"Strategy game with a standard deck of 52 playing cards.","slug":"feud","tags":["card games","feud","friends"],"image":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dopnll2lm/image/upload/v1774639675/feud-testplay_f3goci.jpg","hide_table_of_contents":false},"unlisted":false,"nextItem":{"title":"Quartier chinois","permalink":"/blog/quartier-chinois"}},"content":"I really enjoy the mechanics of collectible card games like [*Magic: The Gathering*](https://magic.wizards.com/en) and [*Disney Lorcana*](https://www.disneylorcana.com/en-US/), but I don\'t like how expensive it can be to build a good deck. It feels pay-to-win for me. So I\'m creating a new card game that is super cheap for everyone to play and focuses on the fun of battling with friends. It\'s called *Feud*.\\r\\n\\r\\n\x3c!-- truncate --\x3e\\r\\n\\r\\n<figure style={{textAlign: \'center\'}}>\\r\\n  <img src=\\"https://res.cloudinary.com/dopnll2lm/image/upload/v1774639675/feud-testplay_f3goci.jpg\\" style={{width: \'70%\'}} />\\r\\n  <figcaption style={{fontSize: \'0.8em\'}}>Testplaying *Feud* with my friends for the first time. March 26, 2026.</figcaption>\\r\\n</figure>\\r\\n\\r\\nIn *Feud*, each of the 2\u20136 players at the table uses the same standard deck of 52 playing cards. No one has an advantage from the get-go because they had more money to pour into booster packs. Standard decks mean equal odds. From there, it\'s up to strategy and chance.\\r\\n\\r\\nHere\'s a summary of how to play. First, you draw a hand of cards and select a face card to be your Ruler. You must protect your Ruler while trying to attack your opponent\'s Ruler. Whoever\'s Ruler falls first, loses.\\r\\n\\r\\nThe remaining cards in the deck can be used as supply or military units like soldiers and archers. The higher the number on a card, the more powerful it is in battle, but also the more supply it costs to deploy. Determining which cards to use as supply, which to use as units, and how to allocate your supply is the game\'s main trade-off and source of fun.\\r\\n\\r\\nDo you deploy low-level units early to rush your opponent? Or are you happy absorbing damage while you stock up for powerful units? Do you favour archers, even though their ranged attacks cost a lot of supply? Or do you like soldiers best, who have limited range but no attack cost?\\r\\n\\r\\n<figure style={{textAlign: \'center\'}}>\\r\\n  <img src=\\"https://res.cloudinary.com/dopnll2lm/image/upload/v1774646996/kangaskhan_w5gwax.jpg\\" style={{width: \'70%\'}} />\\r\\n  <figcaption style={{fontSize: \'0.8em\'}}>Some years ago, my son would find ripped pieces of <i>Pok\xe9mon</i> cards in his schoolyard and ask me to put them back together. I love these cards.</figcaption>\\r\\n</figure>\\r\\n\\r\\nIt\'s still early days for *Feud*. I started working on the game about a month ago, and last night I had a chance to testplay it for the first time with some friends. They gave me great game-improving feedback, and I\'m excited to keep working on the game."},{"id":"quartier-chinois","metadata":{"permalink":"/blog/quartier-chinois","source":"@site/blog/2026-03-22-quartier-chinois.md","title":"Quartier chinois","description":"Montr\xe9al\'s Chinatown.","date":"2026-03-22T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"montreal","permalink":"/blog/tags/montreal"},{"inline":true,"label":"travel","permalink":"/blog/tags/travel"},{"inline":true,"label":"chinatown","permalink":"/blog/tags/chinatown"}],"readingTime":1.5,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[],"frontMatter":{"title":"Quartier chinois","description":"Montr\xe9al\'s Chinatown.","slug":"quartier-chinois","tags":["montreal","travel","chinatown"],"image":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dopnll2lm/image/upload/v1774149999/rue-de-la-gauchetiere_v9bdbb.jpg","hide_table_of_contents":false},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"Feud","permalink":"/blog/feud"},"nextItem":{"title":"Balatro","permalink":"/blog/balatro"}},"content":"I go to Montr\xe9al semi-regularly, like 2\u20133 times a year. These trips tend to be very short. \\r\\n\\r\\n\x3c!-- truncate --\x3e\\r\\n\\r\\nJust a quick there and back if I\'m going to the Montr\xe9al Trudeau airport, or a day trip with the family where we leave in the morning and come home in time for dinner.\\r\\n\\r\\nThis week was the first time I actually spent a night in Montr\xe9al. Two nights, in fact. The hotel was located in the *Quartier chinois* (i.e. Chinatown), smack-dab in the city centre. Great location.\\r\\n\\r\\nI don\'t have much to say about Montr\xe9al. I see a lot of hype for the city online, but I haven\'t fallen in love with it yet. I like that I get to practice my French, though.\\r\\n\\r\\nHere are some pictures I took:\\r\\n\\r\\n<figure style={{textAlign: \'center\'}}>\\r\\n  <img src=\\"https://res.cloudinary.com/dopnll2lm/image/upload/v1774149999/rue-de-la-gauchetiere_v9bdbb.jpg\\" style={{width: \'70%\'}} />\\r\\n  <figcaption style={{fontSize: \'0.8em\'}}>Rue de la Gaucheti\xe8re, as it cuts through Chinatown, where it takes the form of a pedestrian zone. Lots of shops and restaurants.</figcaption>\\r\\n</figure>\\r\\n\\r\\n<figure style={{textAlign: \'center\'}}>\\r\\n  <img src=\\"https://res.cloudinary.com/dopnll2lm/image/upload/v1774149999/snowy-spring_buoker.jpg\\" style={{width: \'70%\'}} />\\r\\n  <figcaption style={{fontSize: \'0.8em\'}}>View from the hotel room. I like how the snow, graffiti, and rooftop units create an urban landscape.</figcaption>\\r\\n</figure>\\r\\n\\r\\n<figure style={{textAlign: \'center\'}}>\\r\\n  <img src=\\"https://res.cloudinary.com/dopnll2lm/image/upload/v1774149999/onur-mural-lightbulb_gw2pcm.jpg\\" style={{width: \'70%\'}} />\\r\\n  <figcaption style={{fontSize: \'0.8em\'}}>Mural by <a href=\\"https://www.onurpainting.com/\\" target=\\"_blank\\">Onur</a>, an artist based in Switzerland. His style is a sort of stylized photorealism. The light bulb apparently <a href=\\"https://streetartnews.net/2017/06/mural-festival-2017-onur-in-montreal.html\\" target=\\"_blank\\">glows in black light</a>, but there\'s no black light installation there anymore.</figcaption>\\r\\n</figure>"},{"id":"balatro","metadata":{"permalink":"/blog/balatro","source":"@site/blog/2026-03-18-balatro.md","title":"Balatro","description":"Just one more run.","date":"2026-03-18T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"balatro","permalink":"/blog/tags/balatro"},{"inline":true,"label":"video games","permalink":"/blog/tags/video-games"},{"inline":true,"label":"card games","permalink":"/blog/tags/card-games"}],"readingTime":2.46,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[],"frontMatter":{"title":"Balatro","description":"Just one more run.","slug":"balatro","tags":["balatro","video games","card games"],"image":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dopnll2lm/image/upload/v1773868520/balatro-shop_sndsui.png","hide_table_of_contents":false},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"Quartier chinois","permalink":"/blog/quartier-chinois"},"nextItem":{"title":"Gabi Hartmann","permalink":"/blog/gabi-hartmann"}},"content":"I love [solitaire games](https://www.microsoftcasualgames.com/solitaire) like Klondike and Spider. When I saw that [*Balatro*](https://www.playbalatro.com/), a poker-adjacent solitaire, was sweeping the Internet, I had to give it a try.\\r\\n\\r\\n\x3c!-- truncate --\x3e\\r\\n\\r\\n<figure style={{textAlign: \'center\'}}>\\r\\n  <img src=\\"https://res.cloudinary.com/dopnll2lm/image/upload/v1773869080/Screenshot_2026-03-18_172319_r801ul.png\\" style={{width: \'70%\'}} />\\r\\n  <figcaption style={{fontSize: \'0.8em\'}}>This is Spider. It tickles my brain.</figcaption>\\r\\n</figure>\\r\\n\\r\\nAs a solitaire, *Balatro* is a playing card game, but I view it essentially as a strategy game. You manage scarce resources to overcome obstacles of increasing difficulty. It\'s easy to learn but very challenging\u2014and very fun\u2014to master. \\r\\n\\r\\nThe game is organized by rounds. You beat a round by making poker hands that generate a minimum amount of points. When you beat the round, you earn some money and advance to the next round, where the points requirement goes up. Every third round, you get a sort of \\"boss round\\" with an added handicap but a larger payout.\\r\\n\\r\\nBetween rounds, you go to the shop. That\'s where you spend money to build your deck. The shop deals a random assortment of Jokers and consummables each time you go there.\\r\\n\\r\\n<figure style={{textAlign: \'center\'}}>\\r\\n  <img src=\\"https://res.cloudinary.com/dopnll2lm/image/upload/v1773868520/balatro-shop_sndsui.png\\" style={{width: \'70%\'}} />\\r\\n  <figcaption style={{fontSize: \'0.8em\'}}><i>Balatro</i>\'s shop.</figcaption>\\r\\n</figure>\\r\\n\\r\\nJokers are the lifeblood of *Balatro*. Each Joker has a unique ability like multiplying points or making money. The consummables\u2014Tarot cards, Planet cards, Spectral cards, and vouchers\u2014improve your performance by doing things like enhancing your cards or powering up poker hands.\\r\\n\\r\\nYou can skip rounds, provided it\'s not a boss round. When you skip a round, you don\'t earn money and you don\'t visit the shop to improve your deck, but you get a tag with a special ability that can help you in other ways.\\r\\n\\r\\nThe trick is knowing how to combine the effects of all these things\u2014Jokers, consummables, and tags\u2014to maximize your points so you can survive a run of 24 rounds. If you make it to the end of the run, you unlock a run of higher difficulty. And on and on it goes.\\r\\n\\r\\nBut if you lose a round, then you lose all your progress and start over from the beginning of the run. In gaming, this genre of unforgiving gauntlet is called *roguelike*.\\r\\n\\r\\n<figure style={{textAlign: \'center\'}}>\\r\\n  <img src=\\"https://res.cloudinary.com/dopnll2lm/image/upload/v1773872249/Screenshot_2026-03-18_181545_wynioh.png\\" style={{width: \'70%\'}} />\\r\\n  <figcaption style={{fontSize: \'0.8em\'}}>I lost. Again.</figcaption>\\r\\n</figure>\\r\\n\\r\\nI initially thought the roguelike aspect would be demotivating, but it isn\'t. When I lose, I\'m always eager to go back and try again. This is because the random Jokers you get early in a run tend to dictate your strategy for the rest of the run, so each run is unique and presents an opportunity to try a new strategy.\\r\\n\\r\\n*Balatro* is super fun. I recommend it."},{"id":"gabi-hartmann","metadata":{"permalink":"/blog/gabi-hartmann","source":"@site/blog/2026-03-14-gabi-hartmann.md","title":"Gabi Hartmann","description":"Eclectic, polyglot jazz.","date":"2026-03-14T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"jazz","permalink":"/blog/tags/jazz"},{"inline":true,"label":"ottawa","permalink":"/blog/tags/ottawa"},{"inline":true,"label":"music","permalink":"/blog/tags/music"},{"inline":true,"label":"nac","permalink":"/blog/tags/nac"}],"readingTime":1.89,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[],"frontMatter":{"title":"Gabi Hartmann","description":"Eclectic, polyglot jazz.","slug":"gabi-hartmann","tags":["jazz","ottawa","music","nac"],"image":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dopnll2lm/image/upload/v1773508909/20260313_201253-2_reorma.jpg","hide_table_of_contents":false},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"Balatro","permalink":"/blog/balatro"},"nextItem":{"title":"Stanley\'s Farm","permalink":"/blog/stanleys-farm"}},"content":"On Friday the 13th, [Gabi Hartmann](https://www.gabihartmannmusic.com/) took the [National Arts Centre](https://nac-cna.ca/en/)\'s [Fourth Stage](https://nac-cna.ca/en/venue/fourth-stage) to present her eclectic, ear-candied brand of jazz.\\r\\n\\r\\n\x3c!-- truncate --\x3e\\r\\n\\r\\nWith her, a trio at the top of their game: [Florian Robin](https://www.instagram.com/florian_robin_kunz/) (piano), [J\xe9r\xf4me Arrighi](https://www.orchestrevictorhugo.fr/artistes/jerome-arrighi/) (bass), and [Arthur Alard](https://www.manusound.net/pages/bio.php?lang=de&mus=_bio/alard_a/) (drums).\\r\\n\\r\\n<figure style={{textAlign: \'center\'}}>\\r\\n  <img src=\\"https://res.cloudinary.com/dopnll2lm/image/upload/v1773531288/20260313_201253_icadkq.jpg\\" style={{width: \'70%\'}} />\\r\\n  <figcaption style={{fontSize: \'0.8em\'}}>Hartmann and the trio.</figcaption>\\r\\n</figure>\\r\\n\\r\\nFor me, Hartmann\'s music is like a **mango sorbet**. It\'s like the tropical and the continental coming together to make something that\'s sweet, smooth, and everyone can enjoy.\\r\\n\\r\\nMuch of her work is inspired by rhythms from Brazil, the Caribbean, and West Africa. A lot of gospel, too. The arrangements are sophisticated, but always accessible. Always voice- and melody-first. And her singing is so silky, even when it occasionally ventures into acrobatics.\\r\\n\\r\\nThe whole show was great, but I had two favourite moments. One was Robin\'s piano solo in \\"[Fall Down](https://youtu.be/3MFZF0PJLoI?si=ksr1-WMsuPRDmq2q),\\" which was full of pointed emotion. He was amazing throughout, as were Arrighi and Alard, but that solo was something else. The other moment was when Hartmann had the audience sing the main lick of \\"[Drink the Ocean](https://youtu.be/Fi16ELXh1XM?si=7Y2O2nq-UvRkqy0m)\\" as a wordless refrain, over and over.\\r\\n\\r\\nI recommend Hartmann\'s music without reservations, both the recordings and seeing it live with the jazz trio, which are quite different experiences.\\r\\n\\r\\n<figure style={{textAlign: \'center\'}}>\\r\\n  <img src=\\"https://res.cloudinary.com/dopnll2lm/image/upload/v1773456618/20260313_213106_cjg268.jpg\\" style={{width: \'70%\'}} />\\r\\n  <figcaption style={{fontSize: \'0.8em\'}}>Hartmann sat on the edge of the stage with the trio to sing her fourth and final encore.</figcaption>\\r\\n</figure>\\r\\n\\r\\nLastly, a word about the venue. The Fourth Stage is a small venue at the NAC. It has all the trappings of a jazz club: atmospheric lighting, unassigned table seating, bar and drinks. The large street-facing windows also add to the ambiance as the bustle of the city bleeds into the venue.\\r\\n\\r\\nOn a snowy night like last night, it was a cool vibe."},{"id":"stanleys-farm","metadata":{"permalink":"/blog/stanleys-farm","source":"@site/blog/2026-03-08-stanleys.md","title":"Stanley\'s Farm","description":"A visit to a sugar bush in late winter.","date":"2026-03-08T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"sugar bush","permalink":"/blog/tags/sugar-bush"},{"inline":true,"label":"ottawa","permalink":"/blog/tags/ottawa"},{"inline":true,"label":"outing","permalink":"/blog/tags/outing"}],"readingTime":1.76,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[],"frontMatter":{"title":"Stanley\'s Farm","description":"A visit to a sugar bush in late winter.","slug":"stanleys-farm","tags":["sugar bush","ottawa","outing"],"image":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dopnll2lm/image/upload/v1773007912/20260307_130123_nmfwec.jpg","hide_table_of_contents":false},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"Gabi Hartmann","permalink":"/blog/gabi-hartmann"},"nextItem":{"title":"Rock, paper, scissors","permalink":"/blog/rock-paper-scissors"}},"content":"This weekend, I visited [Stanley\'s Olde Maple Lane Farm](https://stanleysfarm.com/) with my family. The farm\'s located in Edwards, a rural community south of Ottawa, which I\'d never been to before. It was 8\xb0C and rainy, but we had a good time.\\r\\n\\r\\n\x3c!-- truncate --\x3e\\r\\n\\r\\nStanley\'s main attraction is their sugar bush, which visitors can go through on a tractor ride. The ride was lovely and took a good 15 minutes. It went around much of the farm, not just through the sugar bush, and took us by the fields where the animals were. We saw horses, cows, donkeys, and sheep.\\r\\n\\r\\n<figure style={{textAlign: \'center\'}}>\\r\\n  <img src=\\"https://res.cloudinary.com/dopnll2lm/image/upload/v1773007912/20260307_131748_cot1rx.jpg\\" style={{width: \'70%\'}} />\\r\\n  <figcaption style={{fontSize: \'0.8em\'}}>Detail from a mural at the farm. Love the art style.</figcaption>\\r\\n</figure>\\r\\n\\r\\nWe also saw animals at the barn. There was a two-day-old calf suckling nonstop. The calf\'s tail was up, which we were told was a sign of happiness. And there was a very pregnant ewe lying down in her stall. We could see the lamb(s) kicking inside her. She looked exhausted, but was still a few weeks away from lambing.\\r\\n\\r\\nThere were walking paths through the sugar bush, but we didn\'t take them. We were a little pressed for time and did not dress appropriately for trudging through the mud and melting snow. We were also a little let down that we couldn\'t collect sap from the tapped trees like they let guests do at [The Log Farm](https://thelogfarm.com/).\\r\\n\\r\\n<figure style={{textAlign: \'center\'}}>\\r\\n  <img src=\\"https://res.cloudinary.com/dopnll2lm/image/upload/v1773007912/20260307_130123_nmfwec.jpg\\" style={{width: \'70%\'}} />\\r\\n  <figcaption style={{fontSize: \'0.8em\'}}>Sap vapour rising in the sugar shack.</figcaption>\\r\\n</figure>\\r\\n\\r\\nBut the highlight of the visit was the historical sugar shack. It\'s a structure from the early 20th century that they keep running to entertain guests. The gentleman tending the fire told us it was the first boil of the year. The sweet vapour of evaporating sap permeated the air in and around the shack. It was very special, like being inside a cloud of maple syrup."},{"id":"rock-paper-scissors","metadata":{"permalink":"/blog/rock-paper-scissors","source":"@site/blog/2026-03-02-rock-paper-scissors.md","title":"Rock, paper, scissors","description":"Kindness always wins.","date":"2026-03-02T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"work","permalink":"/blog/tags/work"},{"inline":true,"label":"kindness","permalink":"/blog/tags/kindness"},{"inline":true,"label":"musings","permalink":"/blog/tags/musings"}],"readingTime":1.5,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[],"frontMatter":{"title":"Rock, paper, scissors","description":"Kindness always wins.","slug":"rock-paper-scissors","tags":["work","kindness","musings"],"image":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dopnll2lm/image/upload/v1772463747/20260302_095326_ocva94.jpg","hide_table_of_contents":false},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"Stanley\'s Farm","permalink":"/blog/stanleys-farm"},"nextItem":{"title":"Primeval Well","permalink":"/blog/primeval-well"}},"content":"Lately, I\'ve been under pressure at work. Some of this pressure is caused by people who themselves are under pressure and take out their frustration on me.\\r\\n\\r\\n\x3c!-- truncate --\x3e\\r\\n\\r\\nI believe this sort of trickle-down unkindness is a universal thing. Everyone who works experiences this at some point. I\'m sorry if this sounds jaded.\\r\\n\\r\\nBut personally, I refuse to perpetuate the cycle. I do my darnedest to keep my cool. Don\'t get defensive. Don\'t blame others. Focus on solutions and use words that uplift rather than tear down.\\r\\n\\r\\nI always ask myself, \\"If someone leaked the transcript of this interaction, would my conduct be irreproachable? Would my loved ones feel proud of how I reacted?\\"\\r\\n\\r\\n<figure style={{textAlign: \'center\'}}>\\r\\n  <img src=\\"https://res.cloudinary.com/dopnll2lm/image/upload/v1772463747/20260302_095326_ocva94.jpg\\" style={{width: \'70%\'}} />\\r\\n  <figcaption style={{fontSize: \'0.8em\'}}>I like how the light hits my curtains.</figcaption>\\r\\n</figure>\\r\\n\\r\\nI\'m pushing forty. Technically middle-aged. I\'m not na\xefve. I know anger is a powerful motivator. Anger can bring about change, even necessary change, like nothing else can. Maybe this is what the people who are angry with me think, that by being angry with me, they can spur me to become more competent.\\r\\n\\r\\nBut I don\'t feel that way. I think anger is best directed at _systems_, not _individuals_. I\'ve never solved\u2014_really_ solved\u2014issues with people through anger. Quite the contrary. Some of my deepest regrets come from times when I failed to control my temper.\\r\\n\\r\\nHere\'s what I believe. Remember when we were kids and we\'d play rock, paper, scissors, but add a random fourth element that always beat everything? I think mine was the t-rex. That\'s what kindness is to me. Yes, anger is useful, it can get stuff done, but it can\'t beat kindness. \\r\\n\\r\\nKindness always wins."},{"id":"primeval-well","metadata":{"permalink":"/blog/primeval-well","source":"@site/blog/2026-02-22-primeval-well.md","title":"Primeval Well","description":"Black metal and bluegrass go great together.","date":"2026-02-22T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"primeval well","permalink":"/blog/tags/primeval-well"},{"inline":true,"label":"avant-garde bar","permalink":"/blog/tags/avant-garde-bar"},{"inline":true,"label":"black metal","permalink":"/blog/tags/black-metal"},{"inline":true,"label":"ottawa","permalink":"/blog/tags/ottawa"},{"inline":true,"label":"music","permalink":"/blog/tags/music"}],"readingTime":1.44,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[],"frontMatter":{"title":"Primeval Well","description":"Black metal and bluegrass go great together.","slug":"primeval-well","tags":["primeval well","avant-garde bar","black metal","ottawa","music"],"image":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dopnll2lm/image/upload/v1771817386/igor-profile-2026_z9eyev.png","hide_table_of_contents":false},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"Rock, paper, scissors","permalink":"/blog/rock-paper-scissors"}},"content":"[Primeval Well](https://primevalwell.bandcamp.com/) headlined an intimate show at the [Avant-Garde Bar](https://avantgardebar.myshopify.com/) this past Saturday, February 21, 2026.\\r\\n\\r\\n\x3c!-- truncate --\x3e\\r\\n\\r\\n<figure style={{textAlign: \'center\'}}>\\r\\n  <img src=\\"https://res.cloudinary.com/dopnll2lm/image/upload/v1771816992/20260221_202713_gwhayt.jpg\\" style={{width: \'70%\'}} />\\r\\n  <figcaption style={{fontSize: \'0.8em\'}}>My bathroom selfie at the Avant-Garde.</figcaption>\\r\\n</figure>\\r\\n\\r\\nThe show opened with [Gr\xf3a Willing](https://www.lastingtale.ca/), a local act that plays a sort of minimal, acoustic-only black metal. It was nice. Trance-like. They did four songs, which were all a little samey, but I liked it for what it was.\\r\\n\\r\\nNext up were [Nirthal](https://www.facebook.com/Nirthal), also local and billed as \\"King Diamond worship.\\" I didn\'t care much for their stuff, but others in the audience enjoyed it.\\r\\n\\r\\nPrimeval Well played last. They were **great**. They played selections from their second LP, [*Talkin\' in Tongues with Mountain Spirits*](https://primevalwell.bandcamp.com/album/talkin-in-tongues-with-mountain-spirits) (2021). My favourite tracks were \\"She Flies Undead\\" and \\"Where All Things are Forgotten.\\"\\r\\n\\r\\n<figure style={{textAlign: \'center\'}}>\\r\\n  <img src=\\"https://res.cloudinary.com/dopnll2lm/image/upload/v1771819212/capital-noise/copy_of_20260221_224014_yhjmqw_ce734e.jpg\\" style={{width: \'70%\'}} />\\r\\n  <figcaption style={{fontSize: \'0.8em\'}}>Primeval Well</figcaption>\\r\\n</figure>\\r\\n\\r\\nPrimeval Well\'s shtick is mixing black metal and bluegrass, which sounds like a really strange pairing, but they make it work. They engage with Appalachian folk spirituality so earnestly, it elevates their brand of atmospheric black metal. Full marks from me.\\r\\n\\r\\nA special mention about [Ryan Clackner](https://daily.bandcamp.com/features/ryan-clackner-feature), the band\'s guitarist, vocalist, and main creative force. You get a pretty good idea how inventive and well developed his playing is from the albums, but seeing it live is something else. And a great singer to boot. What a beast."}]}}')}}]);